# ExAIm B2C — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
ExAIm B2C is an AI-powered exam preparation web application for teachers and students.
Always read `project.md` for full context before making any decisions.
Always read the relevant spec file in `spec/` before building any feature.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 16 with App Router
- TypeScript (strict mode — no `any` types ever)
- Tailwind CSS (utility classes only — no inline styles ever)
- shadcn/ui (customised — never use default unstyled components)
- Supabase (database, auth, storage)
- Claude API (AI evaluation and tutor)
- Stripe (payments)
- Resend (emails)
- KaTeX (math rendering)
- TipTap (rich text editor)

## Folder Structure
```
src/
├── app/                  # Next.js App Router pages and layouts
│   ├── (auth)/           # Auth pages (login, signup)
│   ├── (admin)/          # Admin panel routes
│   ├── (teacher)/        # Teacher dashboard routes
│   ├── (student)/        # Student dashboard routes
│   └── api/              # API routes
├── components/
│   ├── ui/               # shadcn/ui base components
│   ├── shared/           # Shared components across roles
│   ├── admin/            # Admin specific components
│   ├── teacher/          # Teacher specific components
│   └── student/          # Student specific components
├── lib/
│   ├── supabase/         # Supabase client and server instances
│   ├── claude/           # Claude API calls and prompts
│   ├── stripe/           # Stripe helpers
│   ├── resend/           # Email templates and sending
│   └── utils/            # General utility functions
├── hooks/                # Custom React hooks
├── types/                # TypeScript types and interfaces
└── constants/            # App wide constants
```

## Coding Rules

### TypeScript
- Strict mode always on
- No `any` types — ever
- All props must be typed with interfaces
- All API responses must be typed
- Use Zod for all form validation and API input validation

### Components
- Functional components only — no class components
- Every component gets its own file
- Component file names are PascalCase e.g. `ExamCard.tsx`
- Keep components small and focused — if it's over 200 lines, split it
- Always handle loading states
- Always handle error states
- Always handle empty states
- Never leave a component without all three states handled

### Styling
- Tailwind utility classes only
- No inline styles ever
- No arbitrary Tailwind values unless absolutely necessary
- Always follow the design system in `spec/design-system.md`
- Mobile styles are not required — desktop first, tablet considered
- Dark mode support required on all components using Tailwind dark: prefix

### API Routes
- All API routes live in `src/app/api/`
- Always validate input with Zod before processing
- Always return consistent response shape:
```typescript
// Success
{ success: true, data: ... }
// Error
{ success: false, error: "message" }
```
- Always handle errors with try/catch
- Never expose internal error messages to the client
- Always check authentication before processing
- Always check authorisation (role) before processing

### Supabase
- Always use server side Supabase client in API routes and server components
- Always use client side Supabase client in client components
- Never expose Supabase service role key to the client
- Always use Row Level Security — never bypass it
- Always use typed Supabase client with generated types

### Authentication & Authorisation
- Every protected route checks auth via middleware
- Every API route checks auth before processing
- Role is always verified — admin, teacher, student
- Never trust client side role claims — always verify from database

### Claude API
- All Claude API calls live in `src/lib/claude/`
- Always use structured JSON output
- Always include error handling for API failures
- Always save student attempt before calling Claude
- If Claude fails, save attempt and retry in background
- Never block the UI waiting for Claude — show processing state
- Always scope AI tutor responses to the student's enrolled course

### Claude API Usage
Claude is used in FOUR distinct ways in this app:

1. **Exam Generation (Admin)**
   - Admin describes an exam, Claude generates full exam with questions, 
     sub-questions, mark schemes and marking points
   - Admin always reviews and approves before publishing
   - Never auto-publish AI generated content
   - All generation calls live in `src/lib/claude/exam-generation.ts`

2. **Question Generation (Admin)**
   - Admin generates individual questions within the exam builder
   - Same review and approval flow applies
   - All generation calls live in `src/lib/claude/question-generation.ts`

3. **Answer Evaluation (Student)**
   - Claude evaluates student answers against mark scheme
   - Returns structured JSON with marks, breakdown, feedback, improvement
   - Vision enabled — images sent alongside question text
   - Error carried forward logic applied for multi-part questions
   - All evaluation calls live in `src/lib/claude/evaluation.ts`

4. **AI Tutor Chatbot (Student)**
   - Post-exam mode: explains mistakes and teaches concepts
   - Standalone mode: student asks questions about their course
   - Always scoped to student's enrolled course — never goes off topic
   - All tutor calls live in `src/lib/claude/tutor.ts`

### Claude API Rules
- Always use claude-sonnet-4-5 model
- Always use structured JSON output for evaluation and generation
- Always include error handling for API failures
- Always save student attempt before calling Claude evaluation
- If Claude fails, save attempt and retry in background
- Never block UI waiting for Claude — always show processing state
- Rate limit all Claude endpoints per user per hour
- Never auto-publish AI generated content — always require human review

### Forms
- Never use HTML `<form>` tags
- Always use controlled components with React state
- Always validate with Zod before submission
- Always show inline validation errors
- Always disable submit button while submitting

### Database
- Never write raw SQL in components or API routes
- Always use Supabase client methods
- All database operations in server side code only
- Never expose database errors to client

### Error Handling
- Every async operation wrapped in try/catch
- User facing errors are always friendly and actionable
- Log detailed errors server side
- Never show stack traces to users

### Code Quality
- No commented out code in commits
- No console.log in production code — use proper logging
- No hardcoded strings — use constants
- No magic numbers — use named constants
- DRY — if you write the same thing twice, extract it

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase — `ExamCard.tsx`
- Files/folders: kebab-case — `exam-card.tsx` for non-components
- Variables/functions: camelCase — `examData`
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE — `MAX_FREE_EXAMS`
- Database tables: snake_case — `exam_attempts`
- Types/interfaces: PascalCase — `ExamAttempt`

## What NOT to Do
- No vibe coding — always read the spec first
- No `any` TypeScript types
- No inline styles
- No skipping loading/error/empty states
- No hardcoded API keys — always use environment variables
- No client side database calls
- No unprotected API routes
- No skipping input validation
- No raw SQL in application code
- No console.log in commits
- No HTML form tags
- No skipping dark mode support
- No arbitrary design decisions — always follow `spec/design-system.md`

## Environment Variables
All secrets live in `.env.local` — never commit this file.
Required variables:
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL`
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY`
- `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`
- `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY`
- `STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET`
- `RESEND_API_KEY`
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL`

## Before Building Any Feature
1. Read `project.md`
2. Read the relevant spec file in `spec/`
3. Read `spec/design-system.md`
4. Check `build-order.md` for current phase
5. Then build